atize marginalized populations by implying that poor health is due to inadequate self-care, despite clear links between health and external factors such as poverty and trauma. This clear-eyed study demonstrates that while we may well celebrate the successes of public health campaigns, they are not without controversy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHealth promotionzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic healthxMoral and ethical aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic healthzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPublic healthzCanadaxMarketingxHistoryy20th century. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh1 aPhilpott, Bethany, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWilmshurst, Sara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311141792940uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483720040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774837200423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774837200/original  a978-3-11-127363-1  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-127598-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-141792-9  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles